# Vercel Web Analytics Integration

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the Next.js App Router project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/analytics` version 1.6.1 using pnpm
- Updated `package.json` with the new dependency
- Updated `pnpm-lock.yaml` with resolved dependencies

### 2. Root Layout Modification (app/layout.tsx)
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next"`
- Inserted `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag, after the `<Providers>` wrapper and `{children}`
- The component is placed at the end of the body to ensure optimal loading without blocking page content

## Implementation Details

**Location:** `app/layout.tsx` (Root Layout for App Router)

**Changes:**
1. Line 5: Added Analytics import from '@vercel/analytics/next'
2. Line 157: Added `<Analytics />` component before closing `</body>` tag

The Analytics component is now active and will automatically track page views and web vitals when the application is deployed to Vercel.

## Verification

- ✅ TypeScript type checking passed (`pnpm run type-check`)
- ✅ No new linting errors introduced by the changes
- ✅ Build compilation started successfully
- ✅ All changes follow Next.js App Router best practices
- ✅ Package.json, pnpm-lock.yaml, and app/layout.tsx staged for commit

## Notes

- The Analytics component is placed after the main content (`{children}`) to ensure it doesn't block rendering
- The component works automatically on Vercel deployments with no additional configuration needed
- Analytics will track page views, web vitals, and custom events once deployed
- The implementation follows the official Vercel Analytics documentation for Next.js App Router projects
